article.description: Katie  Douglas scored 16 points and had five steals as the Orlando Miracle beat the Cleveland Rockers 76-70 in overtime Sunday night.
article.headline: Miracle stay in playoff hunt
article.linkText: Miracle top Rockers in OT to end 3-game skid
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Katie Douglas played with playoff intensity,
knowing her team needed a win to stay in the hunt for a postseason
berth.

	   Douglas scored 16 points and had five steals as the Orlando
Miracle beat the Cleveland Rockers 76-70 in overtime Sunday night.

	   "We were running out of chances and games to get into the
playoffs,'' Douglas said. "That is our ultimate goal, so I think
we focused and came out with a good win. We really wanted this one
and played with a lot of intensity.''

	   Douglas made an off-balance, running one-hander in the lane with
55 seconds left in overtime to put the Miracle ahead 71-67.

	   Nykesha Sales then stole the inbounds pass, was fouled and made
two free throws for a six-point lead and the Miracle went on to
snap a three-game losing streak.

	   "Our defense was the difference,'' Miracle coach Dee Brown
said. "We built an early lead because of good defense. We won at
the end because we got into our zone quickly and made them miss
shots.''

	   Cleveland missed its last four shots of regulation and first
four of overtime.

	   Orlando (11-13) improved to 3-0 in overtime this season,
including a triple-overtime win at home over the Rockers on June 8.
Cleveland (9-16) fell to 0-4 in overtime and lost for the 10th time
in its last 13 games.

	   "Our inability to close out those (overtime) games has impacted
where we are this season,'' Rockers coach Dan Hughes said.

	   Ann Wauters and Chasity Melvin each scored 16 points for
Cleveland, which dropped to 4-9 at home. A year ago, the Rockers
went 14-2 at Gund Arena on the way to winning the Eastern Division.

	   "I never expected this in a million years,'' Rockers guard
Merlakia Jones said. "It's kind of frustrating. How can we get the
wheels turning? It seems that once we start to get there, they fall
off again.''

	   Shannon Johnson scored four of her 15 points as the Miracle went
on a 12-2 run to open the second half, turning a 37-36 deficit into
a 48-39 lead.

	   The Miracle, who lead the WNBA in steals and forced turnovers
per game, twice turned errant Rockers passes into layups during the
run. Orlando had 11 steals and scored 18 points off 16 Rockers
turnovers overall.

	   Helped by a zone defense, Cleveland went on 21-10 spurt for a
60-58 lead with 5:48 left in regulation.

	   Orlando countered with a 3-pointer by Douglas for a 63-62
advantage with four minutes left. Douglas shot 3-for-5 from beyond
the arc overall.

	   Melvin made the second of two free throws with 44 seconds left
for a 65-63 lead.

	   After Wendy Palmer muscled in a layup with 28 seconds left to
tie it at 65, Jones had a chance to win it in regulation, but
missed a 14-footer with two seconds to play.
